		<!-- message -->
		<div>Friss I know of very few warriors over lvl 30 who &quot;do not kick and taunt, who expect to hit A and hold agro no matter what happens&quot;. If that is the case, I suggest immediate use of the disband button - but I suggest you first confirm that it is in fact the case, and not jump to conclusions. I think you may not understand the actual situation. <br />
<br />
I find it difficult to imagine that any warrior who has made it as far as tactics does not use the taunt button. There have been lots of times when I have hit taunt every time it pops in an attempt to peel the mob off of one of my casters, but to no avail - and of course I hear 'don't you know how to TAUNT!!' from the likely-now-dead caster.<br />
<br />
You may not realize this but taunt does NOT work every time it is used - it has to pass a randomized skill check - it is not unusual for a war with max taunt skill to fail 2, 3 even 4 times in a row. You may wish to create a warrior and play through a few levels so you have a better understanding of the capabilities and the limitations of the class?<br />
<br />
My point here is that the very best, most skilled, most well-equipped warrior - the one who throws everything at the aggro problem up to and including the kitchen sink - cannot compare with a dumbass e-bay pally for *consistent* aggro holding. EB is a proc - it goes off as decided by the RNG. Taunt succeeds as decided by the RNG. A pally stun spell is not RNG-dependent - it is reliable and spell based. Therein is the essential issue.<br />
<br />
All that said, there are differences between various warriors - some hold taunt better than others. Gear is a big part of that. Understanding and effectively utilizing the capabilities of the class is another part. If you get a lousy warrior in your group who does not utilize the tools s/he has for holding aggro, that is an easy problem to solve: boot 'em, make a note of the name, do not group with them again. But first be sure that you are not blaming that individual tank for the shortcomings imposed by the RNG.<br />
<br />
Those warriors you love who 'hold aggro' may have just gotten lucky - taunt succeeeded a lot that day. Those 'tell hell warriors' you don't love may have just been unlucky - their taunts were rejected by the almighty RNG.<br />
<br />
But your statement that &quot;The trouble is not holding taunt&quot; is exactly wrong - that is the essential problem.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
