	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Hey Cart:<br />
<br />
So the idea would be for the disc to be always available? Interesting - basically, you could be in hyper-aggro mode at all times, and the price you would pay would be that you would not be able to use any other disc while this was in play? At least, not for 14 minutes in your example. Well, I guess this is better than what I had thought before, but it still leaves the problem as you note, of burst aggro. As you stated:<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				if they gave us the ability to hold agro no matter what it would trivialise so much of the content that actually requires planning. 
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div> <br />
<br />
But don't you see that this is exactly what pallies and SKs have and what makes them superior to us in terms of aggro holding? And I agree that it does trivialize it - and that is a bad thing. <br />
<br />
Put it this way:<br />
<br />
The question is not: 'how good is war aggro holding ability?'. If this were the question, your suggestion would be on target.<br />
<br />
The question really is: 'how good is war aggro holding ability <i>compared to pally/SK aggro holding ability</i> ?'<br />
<br />
So it is not an absolute question - it is a relative question. This is key.<br />
<br />
In other words, the problem with warriors not being able to hold aggro reliably is not that this is such a bad thing - it is that other classes can - so those others classes consistently get picked over war's in planar groups, leading to serious class imbalance.<br />
<br />
Look at it this way: if you were a caster looking for a tank for your group in a tier 2 or higher plane, and you knew that with a (newly disc'd) warrior you would have to use your tashes/slows/nukes/dots cautiously, and you knew that with a pally or SK, you could throw whatever you wanted whenever you wanted and suffer no death as a result - which would you pick? This is the basic problem, and even the implementation of the new disc would not address it, though it would help to alleviate it somewhat. I guess my view would be the suggested disc is a partial workaround, but not a solution.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
